.TH GIT-REWORD 1 "2025-01-01" "git-reword" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
git-reword \- reword git commit messages from files in a directory
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B git-reword
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fImessagedir\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBgit-reword\fR allows you to reword multiple git commit messages by preparing new messages in files named after the commits. Each file in the messagedir should be named after a commit (hash, short hash, or any commitish) and contain the new commit message.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-r\fR, \fB\-\-reset\-author\-date\fR
Update the author date of reworded commits to the current date. By default, the original author date is preserved.
.SH USAGE
1. Prepare a messagedir directory
2. For each commit to reword, create a file named after the commit (hash/ref) containing the new message
3. Run \fBgit-reword messagedir\fR
.SH EXAMPLES
Create a messagedir and reword commits:
.RS
.nf
mkdir messagedir
echo "New commit message" > messagedir/abc1234
git-reword messagedir
.fi
.RE
.PP
Reword commits and update author dates:
.RS
.nf
git-reword -r messagedir
.fi
.RE
.SH REQUIREMENTS
Requires Python 3, git, and git-filter-repo (install with \fBpip install git-filter-repo\fR).
.SH NOTES
- The tool requires a clean working directory (no uncommitted changes)
- Commits are rewritten, so commit hashes will change
- Use with caution on shared repositories
- Original refs are automatically handled by git-filter-repo
